---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import DiscountCalculator from '../../components/calculator/DiscountCalculator.astro';
import Card from '../../components/ui/Card.astro';

const breadcrumbs = [
  { label: 'Home', path: '/' },
  { label: 'Calculators', path: '/all-calculators' },
  { label: 'Discount Percentage Calculator', path: '/calculator/discount-percentage-calculator' }
];
---

<Layout
  title="Discount Percentage Calculator - Calculate Sale Price & Savings"
  description="Free online discount percentage calculator. Calculate final discounted sale prices, original retail costs, markdown percentages, and stacked double coupon saves."
  breadcrumbs={breadcrumbs}
>
  <div class="calculator-page-container container">
    <!-- Interactive Component Slot -->
    <DiscountCalculator />

    <!-- Guide Content Section -->
    <div class="calculator-guide-section" style="margin-top: var(--space-12);">
      
      <!-- Prominent Blog Post Cross-Link Card -->
      <div style="margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">
        <Card elevation="sm" style="border: 1.5px solid var(--color-primary); background-color: var(--color-bg-base); padding: var(--space-5);">
          <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: var(--space-2);">
            <span style="font-size: 0.8rem; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-primary); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.05em;">Featured Retail Math Case Study</span>
            <h3 style="margin: 0; font-size: 1.25rem; font-weight: 800;">The Stacking Coupon Illusion: Why 50% Off + 20% Off Isn't 70%</h3>
            <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95rem; color: var(--color-text-muted); line-height: 1.5;">
              Read a first-person case study of a shopping trip during Black Friday where stacked coupon discounts led to confusion at the register, and learn how to calculate true compound discounts.
            </p>
            <a href="/blog/how-to-calculate-discount-percentage" style="font-weight: 700; font-size: 0.95rem; color: var(--color-primary); margin-top: var(--space-2); display: inline-flex; align-items: center; gap: 4px; width: fit-content; text-decoration: underline;">
              Read: How to Calculate Discount Percentages & Save Money at Checkout
              <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"></line><polyline points="12 5 19 12 12 19"></polyline></svg>
            </a>
          </div>
        </Card>
      </div>

      <div class="prose">
        <h2>How to Calculate Discount Percentages</h2>
        <p>
          Calculating a discount percentage is one of the most practical math skills for daily shopping, household budgeting, and retail management. Whether you are browsing sales tags, applying checkout coupon codes, or calculating clearance markdowns, understanding how percentages work helps you save money and protect your budget.
        </p>
        <p>
          Depending on what information you have, there are three primary ways to calculate a discount:
        </p>

        <h3>1. Finding the Sale Price (Discounted Price)</h3>
        <p>
          If you know the original retail price and the discount percentage (e.g., 20% off a $80 jacket), use this two-step formula:
        </p>
        <p style="text-align: center; font-size: 1.15rem; margin: var(--space-6) 0; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-base);">
          {"\\(\\text{Savings Amount} = \\text{Original Price} \\times \\left(\\frac{\\text{Discount \\%}}{100}\\right)\\)"}
        </p>
        <p style="text-align: center; font-size: 1.15rem; margin: var(--space-6) 0; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-base);">
          {"\\(\\text{Sale Price} = \\text{Original Price} - \\text{Savings Amount}\\)"}
        </p>
        <p>
          For example, a $80 jacket at 20% off:
        </p>
        <p style="text-align: center; font-size: 1.15rem; margin: var(--space-6) 0; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-base);">
          {"\\(\\text{Savings Amount} = \\$80 \\times 0.20 = \\$16.00\\)"}
        </p>
        <p style="text-align: center; font-size: 1.15rem; margin: var(--space-6) 0; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-base);">
          {"\\(\\text{Sale Price} = \\$80 - \\$16 = \\$64.00\\)"}
        </p>

        <h3>2. Finding the Original Price</h3>
        <p>
          If a store lists a sale price of $45 and says it is 10% off, but doesn't show the original price, you can calculate the pre-sale price:
        </p>
        <p style="text-align: center; font-size: 1.15rem; margin: var(--space-6) 0; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-base);">
          {"\\(\\text{Original Price} = \\frac{\\text{Sale Price}}{1 - \\frac{\\text{Discount \\%}}{100}}\\)"}
        </p>
        <p>
          For example, a $45 sale price at 10% off:
        </p>
        <p style="text-align: center; font-size: 1.15rem; margin: var(--space-6) 0; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-base);">
          {"\\(\\text{Original Price} = \\frac{\\$45}{1 - 0.10} = \\frac{\\$45}{0.90} = \\$50.00\\)"}
        </p>

        <h3>3. Finding the Discount Percentage</h3>
        <p>
          If an item was marked down from $150 to $120, you can calculate the markdown percentage:
        </p>
        <p style="text-align: center; font-size: 1.15rem; margin: var(--space-6) 0; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-base);">
          {"\\(\\text{Discount \\%} = \\left(1 - \\frac{\\text{Sale Price}}{\\text{Original Price}}\\right) \\times 100\\)"}
        </p>
        <p>
          For example, marked down from $150 to $120:
        </p>
        <p style="text-align: center; font-size: 1.15rem; margin: var(--space-6) 0; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-base);">
          {"\\(\\text{Discount \\%} = \\left(1 - \\frac{\\$120}{\\$150}\\right) \\times 100 = (1 - 0.80) \\times 100 = 20\\%\\)"}
        </p>

        <h2>The Math Behind Stacking Discounts (Double Discounts)</h2>
        <p>
          Retailers frequently advertise promotions such as "Take 40% off clearance items, plus get an extra 10% off at register."
        </p>
        <p>
          Many shoppers make the mistake of adding these percentages together and expecting a 50% discount. In reality, **stacked discounts are compound, not additive**. 
        </p>
        <p>
          The first discount of 40% is applied to the original retail price. The secondary discount of 10% is then applied *only* to that new, lower intermediate price.
        </p>
        <p>
          For a $100 item:
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>Apply the first 40% discount: $100 × (1 - 0.40) = $60.</li>
          <li>Apply the second 10% discount to $60: $60 × (1 - 0.10) = $54.</li>
          <li>Total Savings = $100 - $54 = $46 (An effective discount of **46%**, not 50%).</li>
        </ol>
        <p>
          Our calculator features a dedicated **Double Discount** mode that models this exact multi-stage progression, showing you the intermediate values and the final net discount rate so you aren't surprised at checkout.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ Section -->
      <div class="calculator-faq-section" style="margin-top: var(--space-10); border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border); padding-top: var(--space-8);">
        <h2 style="font-size: 1.5rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">Discount Calculator Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        
        <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: var(--space-4);">
          <details style="background: var(--color-bg-base); border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4);" open>
            <summary style="font-weight: 700; cursor: pointer; outline: none; user-select: none;">Does the calculator support tax additions?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: var(--space-2); font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.5; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
              Currently, this calculator focuses strictly on retail markdowns and saving calculations. Because sales tax varies widely by state, province, and product category, we recommend calculating your final discounted price here, and then multiplying that price by your local tax rate (e.g., multiply by 1.08 for an 8% sales tax).
            </p>
          </details>

          <details style="background: var(--color-bg-base); border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4);">
            <summary style="font-weight: 700; cursor: pointer; outline: none; user-select: none;">Why do stores use stacked discounts instead of flat percentages?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: var(--space-2); font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.5; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
              Stores use stacked discounts (e.g., "50% off + 20% off") for two main reasons: 1) **Psychology:** "50% + 20%" sounds like a massive 70% off to casual shoppers, inducing urgency, and 2) **Margin Protection:** It is mathematically cheaper for the retailer. Offering 50% and then 20% sequentially translates to a 60% total reduction, protecting the store's margins by 10% compared to a flat 70% off.
            </p>
          </details>

          <details style="background: var(--color-bg-base); border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4);">
            <summary style="font-weight: 700; cursor: pointer; outline: none; user-select: none;">How do you convert a fraction into a discount percentage?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: var(--space-2); font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.5; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
              If a store offers "Buy 3, Get 1 Free", you are getting 1 item free out of a total of 4 items. The fraction is 1/4. Convert this to a decimal by dividing the numerator by the denominator (1 / 4 = 0.25) and multiply by 100 to get a **25% discount**.
            </p>
          </details>

          <details style="background: var(--color-bg-base); border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4);">
            <summary style="font-weight: 700; cursor: pointer; outline: none; user-select: none;">Is there a difference between markdown, discount, and margin?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: var(--space-2); font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.5; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
              Yes. A **discount** or **markdown** refers to the reduction of a product's retail price for the customer (e.g., 20% off). **Gross Margin** refers to the percentage of profit a merchant makes on a sale relative to their cost of sourcing the item. 
            </p>
          </details>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>

<style>
  .calculator-page-container {
    max-width: 1000px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-4);
  }

  .prose h2 {
    font-size: 1.5rem;
    font-weight: 800;
    margin-top: var(--space-8);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    color: var(--color-text-base);
  }

  .prose h3 {
    font-size: 1.2rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    margin-top: var(--space-5);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2.5);
    color: var(--color-text-base);
  }

  .prose p {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
  }

  .prose ul, .prose ol {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
    padding-left: var(--space-6);
  }

  .prose li {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    line-height: 1.6;
  }
</style>
